Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
addRepeaterByRule(25.10)                              addRepeaterByRule(25.10)

Name
       addRepeaterByRule  -  Inserts  buffers and/or inverters to nets, as de-
       fined in a rule file

Syntax
       addRepeaterByRule

       [-help]

       [-allowMixedSignal]

       [-copyNetAttribute]

       [-excNet <excludeNetFile>]

       [-netMapping <fileName>]

       [-nets <list_of_nets>]

       [-outDir <directoryName>]

       [-preRoute | -postRoute | -alongRoute]

       [-reportIgnoredNets <ignoredNetFile>]

       [-rule <fileName>]

       [-selNet <selNetFile>]

       [-selected]

       [-template]

       Inserts buffers and/or inverters to nets, as defined in a rule file. By
       default, inserts available buffers and/or inverters with  the  smallest
       total  area cost while satisfying the rules. As compared to DRV fixing,
       addRepeaterByRule does not consider transition violations (maxTran)  or
       any  timing  information.  Instead, it constrains max total net length,
       max radius length, max capacitance, max fanout count, and so on.  Also,
       addRepeaterByRule   does  not legalize newly added buffers. You need to
       legalize the added buffers to a legal location.

       The command provides an efficient, buffering method for  top-level  de-
       signs.

       Note: Max radius length refers to the sum of wire lengths from the dri-
       ver  to  the farthest sink and max total net length refers to the total
       (sum) wire lengths throughout the target net.

       The command has the following features:

              *

                Supports multiple buffer/inverter/AO cells simultaneously

              *

                Supports multiple types of constrains simultaneously

              *

                Provides complete MSV compatibility solution

              *

                It is multithreaded

       The rule file may contain two categories  of  constraints,  where  each
       category  further  breaks  down  to  several constraint types. All con-
       straints share the same syntax of `command value'.

       1. Individual repeaters' rule: constrains each repeater's driving capa-
       bility.

              * max net total length (um): SetInverterMaxNetLength, SetBuffer-
                MaxNetLength,  SetBufferMinLayerMaxNetLength,  SetInverterMin-
                LayerMaxNetLength

              * max radius length (um): SetInverterMaxRadiusLength, SetBuffer-
                MaxRadiusLength

              * max capacitance (pF): SetInverterMaxCap, SetBufferMaxCap

              * max fanout count: SetInverterMaxFanout, SetBufferMaxFanout

              * max fanout at sink count: SetMaxFanoutAtSink

              * max  wirelength  (um)  of  the net driving the sink term: Set-
                MaxNetLengthAtSink

        2. Global default rule: constrains all other  instances  beyond  those
       newly inserted repeater instances.

              * default  max  net  total  length (um): SetDefaultMaxNetLength,
                SetDefaultMinLayerMaxNetLength

              * default max radius length(um): SetDefaultMaxRadiusLength

              * default max cap length (pF): SetDefaultMaxCap

              * default max fanout count: SetDefaultMaxFanout

              * default max sink radius length (um): SetDistLastRepToSink

              * default max wirelength (um) of the net driving the sink  term:
                SetMaxNetLengthAtSink

       Those  constraints  can  be  used individually or combined. However, at
       least one valid repeater must be specified in the  rule  file.  If  the
       global  default  rule  for  certain constraint type is omitted from the
       rule file, the command automatically picks the tightest constraint from
       the repeaters defined in the rule file under  the  same  type  of  con-
       straint  as  the default constraint. A sample rule file is shown in the
       "Example" section.

       The following three layer-based rules are provided to support  specify-
       ing net length constraints independently for each user specified layer:

              * minimum  layer for max net total length (um): SetBufferMinLay-
                erMaxNetLength and SetInverterMinLayerMaxNetLength

              * default minimum layer for max net total  length  (um):  SetDe-
                faultMinLayerMaxNetLength

       Note:  You  must  specify  the  bottom_preferred_routing_layer/top_pre-
       ferred_routing_layer attribute  for  the  nets  that  need  layer-based
       buffering.   If  no  attribute is present, the net will be routed  with
       the default rule on default layers.

       Use Model

       When max layer constraint is specified:

       SetBufferMaxNetLength BUF_X4M_A9TR 300.0

       In the above scenario, ARR will buffer the  net  with  BUF_X4M_A9TR  at
       length intervals of 300um.

       When  minimum layer support is also specified along with max layer con-
       straint, then the following two scenarios are possible:

       Example 1:

       SetBufferMaxNetLength          BUF_X4M_A9TR     300.0

       SetBufferMinLayerMaxNetLength  BUF_X4M_A9TR 6   500.0

       In the above example,  layers 2-5 will have a 300um max length, and be-
       casue there is a minimum layer constraint on the  net  of  layer  6  or
       higher, the length constraint will be increased from 300 to 500um.

       Example 2:

       When multiple minimum layer constraints are specified:

       SetBufferMaxNetLength            BUF_X4M_A9TR     300.0

       SetBufferMinLayerMaxNetLength    BUF_X4M_A9TR 6   500.0

       SetBufferMinLayerMaxNetLength    BUF_X4M_A9TR 11  800.0

       In  the  above example, layers 2-5 will have a 300um max length; layers
       6-9 will have a 500um max length;  and  11+  will  have  an  800um  max
       length.

Parameters
       -help  Outputs  a  brief description that includes type and default in-
              formation for each addRepeaterByRule parameter. For  a  detailed
              description  of  the  command and all of its parameters, use man
              addRepeaterByRule.

       -allowMixedSignal
              When specified, allows buffering on mixed signal nets.

       -alongRoute
              Allows repeater insertion along the route. The  database  should
              be global-routed with preRoute RC extraction before calling this
              option.

              Note:  Run  refinePlace and ecoRoute if you specify this parame-
              ter.

       -copyNetAttribute
              When this parameter is specified, the net attributes set on  the
              original nets are copied to the nets inserted by this command.

       -excNet <fileName>
              Specifies a file that contains the names of hierarchical nets to
              exclude  from  rule  violation  repair.  If a net appears in the
              files specified by both -excNet and -selNet, it is excluded from
              rule violation repair.

       -netMapping <fileName>
              When specified, generates a file  that  maps  the  original  net
              names  to  the  nets inserted by this command. An example of the
              file format is provided below. In this example,  netA  is  split
              into two nets: FE_new_net1_netA and FE_new_net2_netA.

               netA FE_new_net1_netA

               netA FE_new_net2_netA

              If,  in the next iteration, FE_new_net1_netA is split again, the
              file    would     contain     the     following:FE_new_net1_netA
              FE_new_net1_FE_new_net1_netA

               FE_new_net1_netA FE_new_net2_FE_new_net1_netA

       -nets <list_of_nets>
              Specifies  the  list of nets to be considered for adding buffers
              and/or inverters.

              Note: The -nets, -selNet, and -selected parameters are  mutually
              exclusive.

       -outDir <directoryName>
              Specifies the directory where the software writes detailed fail-
              ure  reason  report that is generated when this command runs. By
              default, the failure reason report is dumped  in  the  timingRe-
              ports/ARRFailureReason/<design> directory. For example,

              timingReports/ARRFailureReason/<design>.arr.preRoute.rpt.gz

              Default: timingReports

       -postRoute
              Allows  repeater  insertion along the route. The database should
              be detailed-routed with detailed RC  extraction  before  calling
              this option. Preserves routing so that changes are minimized.

              Note: Run refinePlace  and ecoRoute  if you specify this parame-
              ter.

       -preRoute
              Allows repeater insertion with different routing topologies. The
              database should be global-routed with preRoute RC extraction be-
              fore calling this option.

               When this parameter is specified, the software explores differ-
              ent typologies to optimally insert repeaters.

       -reportIgnoredNets <fileName>
              Reports  the  nets where no buffers were inserted and the reason
              the nets were ignored.

       -rule <fileName>
              Specifies a file you create that should list the buffers and in-
              verters and the length and capacitance rules for inserting  each
              of  them.  Only  buffers and inverters included in the rule file
              are inserted.

       -selected
              When this parameter is specified, the addRepeaterByRule  command
              operates  only on nets that are selected either by the selectNet
              command or in the GUI.

              Note: The -nets, -selNet, and -selected parameters are  mutually
              exclusive.

       -selNet <fileName>
              Specifies  a  file  that contains the names of hierarchical nets
              considered by this command. If a net appears in the files speci-
              fied by both  -excNet  and  -selNet , it is excluded  from  rule
              violation repair.

              Note:  The -nets, -selNet, and -selected parameters are mutually
              exclusive.

       -template
              Writes a template rule file.

              Note: When the -template parameter is  specified,  the  software
              does not honor any other parameters for this command.

Examples
              * The  following  command explores different typologies to opti-
                mally insert repeaters:

                addRepeaterByRule -rule rule1 -preRoute

              * In a detailed routed database with RC extraction, the  follow-
                ing  command  inserts  repeaters along the route and preserves
                routing, so that changes are minimized:

                addRepeaterByRule -rule rule1 -postRoute

              * The following command inserts repeaters on those  nets  speci-
                fied in the file, net_file1:

                addRepeaterByRule -rule rule1 -selNet net_file1

              * The following is an example of a template rule file:

                ##########################################################################

                ###################   addRepeaterByRule   template  rule  file
                ####################

                #############################################################################

                # constraintType             cellName               constraint
                value

                #
                Length(um)/cap(pF)/count

                #############################################################################

                ########### max net total Lengths for individual repeaters

                  SetInverterMaxNetLength    HS65_LH_IVX7         150.0

                  SetBufferMaxNetLength      HS65_LS_BFX7         300.0

                ########### max radius Lengths for individual repeaters

                  SetInverterMaxRadiusLength HS65_LH_IVX7         100.0

                  SetBufferMaxRadiusLength   HS65_LS_BFX7         240.0

                ########### max capacitance for individual repeaters

                  SetInverterMaxCap         HS65_LH_IVX7          10.0

                  SetBufferMaxCap           HS65_LS_BFX7          20.0

                ########### max fanout for individual repeaters

                  SetInverterMaxFanout      HS65_LH_IVX7          20

                  SetBufferMaxFanout        HS65_LS_BFX7          30

                ########### default max net total Lengths

                  SetDefaultMaxNetLength                          100.0

                ########### default max radius Lengths

                  SetDefaultMaxRadiusLength                       200.0

                ########### default max capacitance

                  SetDefaultMaxCap                                15.0

                ########### default sink max radius length

                  SetDistLastRepToSink                            50.0

                ########### max net lengths from sink

                   SetMaxNetLengthAtSink                           100.0

                ########### default max fanout

                  SetDefaultMaxFanout                             20

                ################################################################################
                'DrivingStrength'  constrains  both  max radius Length and max
                cap.
                ################################################################################
                constraintType                cellName              Length(um)
                cap(pF)
                ###############################################################################
                SetInverterDrivingStrength       HS65_LH_IVX7            100.0
                10.0            SetBufferDrivingStrength          HS65_LS_BFX7
                240.0                20.0            SetDefaultDrivingStrength
                200.0           15.0

